ns]]''', journalist, writer, [[linguistics|linguist]], and scholar<ref name=\"visitponce\"/><ref>[http://www.enciclopediapr1.org/ing/article.cfm?ref=10011901 ]{{dead link|date=March 2014}}</ref>\n* '''[[Luis L\u00f3pez Nieves]]''', writer<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ciudadseva.com/libros/ponce.htm |title=La verdadera muerte de Juan Ponce de Le\u00f3n - Luis L\u00f3pez Nieves |publisher=Ciudadseva.com |date=7 May 2011 |accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref>\n* '''[[\u00c1ngel Lozada]]''', novelist<ref>{{cite journal|last=Villanueva Collado |first=Alfredo |url=https://www.redalyc.org/pdf/377/37719110.pdf |title=Ren\u00e9 Marqu\u00e9s, Angel Lozada, and the Constitution of the (Queer) Puerto Rican National Subject |publisher=CENTRO Journal 19:1 (Spring 2007), 179&ndash;191 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120923055717/http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/pdf/377/37719110.pdf |archivedate=23 September 2012 }}</ref>\n* '''[[Carmen Lugo Filippi]]''' (born 1940), short-story writer<ref name=Torres/>\n{{div col end}}\n\n==M-N==\n{{div col}}\n* '''[[Manuel Manrique]]''', novelist, author of ''Island in Harlem'' (1966)<ref name=Zimmerman/>\n* '''[[Hugo Margenat]]''', poet<br />Margenat was also the founder of the political youth pro-independence organizations \"Acci\u00f3n Juventud Independentista\" and \"Federaci\u00f3n de Universitarios Pro Independencia\".<ref name=\"EPR\">{{cite web |url=http://www.enciclopediapr.org/ing/article.cfm?ref=06100601&page=5 |title=Language and Literature: Brief History of Puerto Rican Literature |publisher=Enciclopediapr.org |accessdate=12 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113133453/http://www.enciclopediapr.org/ing/article.cfm?ref=06100601&page=5 |archivedate=13 January 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''[[Ren\u00e9 Marqu\u00e9s]]''', playwright<br />''Marqu\u00e9s wrote \"La Carreta\" (The Oxcart) which helped secure his reputation as a leading literary figure in Puerto Rico.''<ref name=\"A\">https://journals.ku.edu/index.php/latr/article/viewFile/63/38</ref> \n* '''[[Manuel Mart\u00ednez Maldonado]]''' (born 1937), physician, poet, novelist, author of poetry books ''La voz sostenida'' and ''La novela del medio d\u00eda'' and of the novel ''Isla Verde''<ref name=\"Fm\">http://medicine-opera.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/03/martines-founders-medal-presentation.pdf</ref>\n* '''[[Antonio Martorell]]''' (born 1939), painter, graphic artist, writer and radio and television personality<ref name=Torres/>\n* '''[[Nemir Matos-Cintr\u00f3n]]''', poet, novelist<ref>Rodr\u00edguez-Matos, Carlos Antonio. \"Matos-Cintr\u00f3n, Nemir.\" In ''Latin American Writers on Gay and Lesbian Themes'', ed. David William Foster, 216\u201317. Westport, Conn.: Greenwood Press, 1994.</ref>\n* '''[[Francisco Matos Paoli]]''', poet, critic, and essayist<br />''Matos Paoli was nominated for the [[Nobel Prize in literature]] in 1977. He was also a Secretary General of the [[Puerto Rican Nationalist Party]].''<ref name=\"PC\">{{cite web|author=Daniel B. Zwickel |url=http://www.peacehost.net/WhiteStar/Voices/eng-matos.html |title=Francisco Matos Paoli |publisher=Peacehost.net |date= |accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref>\n* '''[[Joserram\u00f3n Melendes]]''' (born 1952), poet<ref name=Torres/>\n* '''[[Concha Melendez]]''', poet, writer<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icp.gobierno.pr/bge/bge_concha.htm |accessdate=14 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205072531/http://www.icp.gobierno.pr/bge/bge_concha.htm |archivedate=5 February 2012 }}</ref>\n* '''[[Jes\u00fas Papoleto Mel\u00e9ndez]]''', poet<ref name=Zimmerman/>\n* '''[[Manuel M\u00e9ndez Ballester]]''', writer<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.agproxy.inter.edu/cai/salamuseo_mmb.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040409043649/http://agproxy.inter.edu/cai/salamuseo_mmb.htm |archivedate=9 April 2004 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''[[Nancy Mercado]]''', poet, playwright<br />''Mercado is the author of \"It Concerns the Madness,\" seven theatre plays, and a number of essays. Her work has been extensively anthologized.''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbwire.com/press-releases/arts/literature/sbwire-116151.htm |title=phati'tude Literary Magazine Announces Guest Editor |publisher=Sbwire.com |date=28 November 2011 |accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref>\n* '''[[Luis Mu\u00f1oz Mar\u00edn]]''', politician and poet\n* '''[[Nicholasa Mohr]]''', writer<br />''Her works, among which is the novel ''Nilda'', tell of growing up in the Puerto Rican communities of the [[Bronx]] and [[Spanish Harlem|El Barrio]] and of the difficulties Puerto Rican women face in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bookrags.com/biography/nicholasa-mohr-dlb/ |title=Nicholasa Mohr Biography |publisher=BookRags.com |date=2 November 2010 |accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Paul Lauter, General Editor |url=http://college.hmco.com/english/lauter/heath/4e/students/author_pages/contemporary/mohr_ni.html |title=Heath Anthology of American Literature Nicholasa Mohr - Author Page |publisher=College.hmco.com |date= |accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref>\n* '''[[Rosario Morales]]''', poet, co-author of ''Getting Home Alive'' (1986)<ref name=Zimmerman/>\n* '''[[Luis Negr\u00f3n]]''', short-story writer<br />''His book ''Mundo Cruel'' won the [[Lambda Literary Award for Gay Fiction]] at the [[26th Lambda Literary Awards]] in 2014.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambdaliterary.org/reviews/03/05/mundo-cruel-by-luis-negron/|title='Mundo Cruel' by Luis Negr\u00f3n|last=Lopez|first=Dan|date=2013-03-06|website=Lambda Literary|access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref>\n* '''[[Mercedes Negron Mu\u00f1oz]]''', a.k.a. \"[[Clara Lair]]\", poet<br />''Negr\u00f3n Mu\u00f1oz was an influential poet whose work dealt with the everyday struggles of the common Puerto Rican.''<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=b65NtSSss3cC&pg=PA234&lpg=PA234&dq=mercedes+negron+munoz |title=Puerto Rico Past and Present: An Encyclopedia - Ronald Fernandez, Seraf\u00edn M\u00e9ndez M\u00e9ndez, Gail Cueto - Google Boeken |access-date=12 March 2014|isbn=9780313298226 |year=1998 |last1=Fernandez |first1=Ronald |last2=Mendez |first2=Seraf\u00edn Mendez |last3=Cueto |first3=Gail }}</ref>\n* '''[[Urayo\u00e1n Noel]]''', poet<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poets/urayoan-noel|title=Urayo\u00e1n Noel - Poetry Foundation|website=Poetry Foundation|access-date=2019-06-24}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n==O==\n{{div col}}\n* '''[[Judith Ortiz Cofer]]''', poet, writer and essayist<ref name=\"joc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.libs.uga.edu/gawriters/cofer.html |title=Georgia Writers Hall of Fame &#124; Home |publisher=Libs.uga.edu |date= |accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref>\n* '''[[Micol Ostow]]''', author<br /> ''Ostow wrote ''Mind Your Manners, Dick and Jane''. Her novel ''Emily Goldberg Learns to Salsa'' was named a New York Public Library Book for the Teen Age.''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.princeton.lib.nj.us/children/festival/2007AuthorsAttending.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=6 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100226235452/http://www.princeton.lib.nj.us/children/festival/2007AuthorsAttending.htm |archivedate=26 February 2010 }}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n==P-Q==\n{{div col}} \n*'''[[Jos\u00e9 Gualberto Padilla]]''' a.k.a. \"El Caribe\", poet<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bibliotecavirtualut.suagm.edu/elibros/LibroPR/LPR_Esp/Capitulo%20_XVIII_HOMBRE_DEL_PASADO.pdf |language=Spanish |title=XVIII Hombre del Pasado |first=Eugenio |last=Astol |publisher=Bibliotecavirtualut.suagm.edu |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425080044/http://bibliotecavirtualut.suagm.edu/elibros/LibroPR/LPR_Esp/Capitulo%20_XVIII_HOMBRE_DEL_PASADO.pdf |archivedate=25 April 2012 }}</ref>\n* '''[[Reggie R. Padin]]''', writer, educator, ordained minister, author of ''Get Out of the Dum