{"title_page": "Ken Nwadiogbu", "text_new": "{{short description|Nigerian visual artist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Ken Nwadiogbu\n| image       = Ken Nwadiogbu\u2019s Profile picture.jpg\n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = Kenechukwu Emmanuel Nwadiogbu\n| birth_place = Nigerian\n| occupation  = Visual artist\n| movement    = Contemporealism\n| website     = {{URL|www.kennwadiogbu.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Ken Nwadiogbu''' (popularly known as '''KenArt''') is a Nigerian born multidisciplinary artist.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/videos/world/2018/04/03/ken-nwadiogbu-lagos-hyperrealist.cnn/|title=Ken Nwadiogbu: Nigeria's groundbreaking, hyperrealist artist|work=CNN|access-date=2018-04-05}}</ref> He calls his method contemporealism \u2013 a fusion that is primarily centered around [[Hyperrealism (visual arts)|hyper-realism]] and [[contemporary art]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kennwadiogbu.com/statement/|title=Ken Nwadiogbu: Artist Statement|work=kennwadiogbu official website|access-date=2018-04-05}}</ref> In 2019, Ken Nwadiogbu was awarded the prestigious [[The Future Awards Africa]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://awards.thefutureafrica.com/burna-boy-israel-adesanya-timini-egbuson-simi-drey-adejumo-tolani-alli-others-emerge-winners-at-the-future-awards-africa-2019/|title=winners at The Future Awards Africa 2019|work=TFAA 2019|access-date=2019-11-26}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nKenechukwu Nwadiogbu did not set out to become an artist. Born at a time when parents still choose professions for their children and fields in science were deemed the most lucrative, Nwadiogbu wanted to study civil engineering. Although, this 17-year-old Nwadiogbu's life is about to change as he discovers art in the most intriguing way- puppy love.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://guardian.ng/life/ken-nwadiogbu-the-rise-of-nigerias-contemporealist/|title=Ken Nwadiogbu: The Rise Of Nigeria\u2019s Contemporealist|work=Guardian Life|access-date=2019-09-29}}</ref>\n\nAs he developed in his drawing, his fame among his small circle grew and the encouragement from his friends spurred him on.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://guardian.ng/life/ken-nwadiogbu-the-rise-of-nigerias-contemporealist/|title=Ken Nwadiogbu: The Rise Of Nigeria\u2019s Contemporealist|work=Guardian Life|access-date=2019-09-29}}</ref>\n\nNwadiogbu attended the [[University of Lagos]], where he studied [[Civil Engineering|Civil and Environmental Engineering]]. His journey with art began in this university, and despite having no formal training, he has pushed to become an interesting contemporary artist from [[Nigeria]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thesparkng.com/hyper-realistic-drawings-kenart/|title=Hyper-realistic drawings by Kenart|work=The Spark|access-date=2018-04-04}}</ref>\n\n==Style of art==\nAccording to an interview with [[Juxtapoz Magazine]], Nwadiogbu responds on canvas to socio-political structures and issues around him and the world. Through meticulous hyperrealist technique, he constructs arresting images rich with deft use of form and space. Cleverly, his paintings regularly feature obscure portraits of everyday people peeking through the ripped paper, elevating and situating Africans in the global context. Weighty issues like gender equality, African cultures, global politics, Black power, and most recently knife-crime come to the conversation by way of his mind-boggling technique.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.juxtapoz.com/news/painting/ken-nwadiogbu-opens-his-international-debut-brick-lane-gallery-london/|title=Ken Nwadiogbu Opens His International Debut at Brick Lane Gallery, London|work=JUXTAPOZ MAGAZINE|date=2019-09-26}}</ref> Working with charcoal, pencil, and acrylic, Nwadiogbu aims to achieve a deeper meaning through his art, one which goes beyond the visually spectacular facade he presents into different themes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boredpanda.com/hyper-realistic-drawings-ken-nwadiogbu-nigeria/|title=This Nigerian Artist\u2019s Artworks Are So Realistic It\u2019s Hard To Believe He Used Nothing More Than A Pencil|work=Bored Panda|access-date=2018-02-16}}</ref>\n\nHis art is inspired by social movements and principles while evaluating, interrogating and challenging socio-political structures and issues within society. He perceives his art as a response to society and a way to inspire one or two people to re-evaluate their socio-political structures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.creativeboom.com/inspiration/ken-nwadiogbu-addresses-race-and-gender-with-his-hyperrealist-art/|title=Ken Nwadiogbu addresses issues of race and gender with his 'contemporealist' art|work=Creative Boom|date=2019-10-01}}</ref>\n\n===A Voice for #MeToo===\nAccording to an interview with [[CNN]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition-m.cnn.com/2018/04/06/africa/ken-nwadiogbu-hyperrealist-artist-nigeria-africa/|title=Ken Nwadiogbu: Inside Nigeria's hyperrealist art scene|work=CNN|access-date=2018-04-11}}</ref> Nwadiogbu's most recent work was a piece for the global #MeToo movement\u2014a work he's so passionate about, he completed it within 24 hours. In the #MeToo piece, two girls are wrapped in nylon, one is depressed and resigned to her fate; the other is angry and determined to push through the barrier. It's an emotional piece, born from thoughtfulness and his passion to give young African girls a voice.\n\n\"I want the African girl to be like the second girl (in the painting) who is saying, 'I want to speak out. I want to loud my consciousness. I want to loud who I am.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition-m.cnn.com/2018/04/06/africa/ken-nwadiogbu-hyperrealist-artist-nigeria-africa/|title=Ken Nwadiogbu: Inside Nigeria's hyperrealist art scene|work=CNN|access-date=2018-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and residencies==\n*2019: [[The Future Awards Africa]] Prize for Art (Visual/Applied)<ref>[https://www.herald.ng/2019-future-awards-africa-winners/\"2019 Future Awards Africa \u2013 Complete List of Winners\"], The Herald. 25 November 2019.</ref>\n*2019: The Bridgeman Studio Award (Grand Prize winner)<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.bridgemanimages.co.uk/en/12695/bridgeman-studio-award-2019-winner-ken-nwadiogbu-interview/|title= Bridgeman Studio Award 2019 Winner: Ken Nwadiogbu Interview|access-date=2020-01-20|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions==\n* 2016, ''Insanity''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2016/12/creating-platform-devt-young-artists-frank-momoh/|title=We\u2019re creating platform for devt of young artists \u2014Frank Momoh - Vanguard News|date=2016-12-17|work=Vanguard News|access-date=2018-02-07}}</ref>- Sponsored by Frot Foundation. Held at [[Omenka Gallery]], Ikoyi, Lagos, Nigeria.\n* 2017, ''It's Not Furniture''<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pulse.ng/lifestyle/food-travel-arts-culture/its-not-furniture-exhibition-reveals-art-as-a-representation-of-young-contemporary-individuals-id6717009.html|title=It\"s Not Furniture: Exhibition reveals art as a representation of young contemporary individuals|last=Omotosho|first=Kehinde|access-date=2018-02-07}}</ref> - Sponsored by Temple Management Company. Held at Omenka Gallery,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://visual.ng/2017/05/25/its-not-furniture-exhibition-opens-at-omenka-gallery-in-lagos/|title=\u2018It\u2019s NOT furniture\u2019 exhibition opens at Omenka Gallery in Lagos|date=2017-05-25|work=Visual Magazine|access-date=2018-02-07}}</ref> Ikoyi, Lagos, Nigeria.\n* 2017, ''Finding your Identity'' - Sponsored by ENACOF. Held at British Council, Abuja, Nigeria.\n* 2017, ''ARTYRAMA'' Art Exhibition<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thisdaylive.com/index.php/2017/12/09/artyrama-hosts-digital-art-gallery/|title=Artyrama Hosts Digital Art Gallery|last=Editor|first=Online|date=2017-12-09|work=THISDAYLIVE|access-date=2018-02-07}}</ref>- Curated by Jess Castellote. Held at Alhaji Bashorun, Ikoyi, Lagos, Nigeria.\n* 2018, ''EMPOWERMENT'' Exhibition<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.creativedebuts.co.uk/exhibitions/nasty-women-exhibition-empowerment/|title=Nasty Women Exhibition: Empowerment|last=Debut|first=Creative|access-date=2018-03-27}}</ref> - By Creative Debuts and Nasty Women NYC. Held at Black and White Building, Rivington Street, London.\n* 2018, ''Generation'' Y<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://retroafrica.com/portfolio/generation-y/|title=Generation Y- A Contemporary Art Exhibition|work=Retro Africa|access-date=2018-04-05}}</ref>- A Contemporary Art Exhibition by Retro Africa. Held at The Exhibition Pavilion, Abuja, Nigeria.\n* 2018, ''Moniker'' Art Fair<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.monikerartfair.com/projects/creative-debuts/|title=Moniker Art Fair|work=Creative Debut|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref>- A Contemporary Art Fair sponsored by Creative Debuts and held at Greenpoint Terminal Warehouse, Brooklyn, NYC.\n* 2018, ''Anti Trump'' Art Show<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://fadmagazine.com/2018/07/08/anti-trump-art-show/|title=Anti Trump Art Show|work=FAD Magazine|access-date=2018-07-08}}</ref>- A contemporary art show about the \u2018dangerous racism, sexism and narcissism that flow daily from the White House,' held at the July Rivington Studios, 1 Bath Place, Shoreditch London.\n* 2018, ''Afriuture Exhibition''- By Ramati Art Africa in association with the Commonwealth Africa Summit. Held at the Ontario Investment and Trade centre, Toronto, Canada.\n* 2018, ''Art X'' Lagos<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://artxlagos.com/artists/ken-nwadiogbu/|title=Art X Lagos|work=Artyrama Gallery|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref>- First International Contemporary Art Fair in West Africa held at Federal Palace, Lagos, Nigeria.\n* 2019, ''LAX-SFO''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thinkspaceprojects.com/shows/lax-sfo-iii/|title=LAX / SFO Pt. III|work=Thinkspace Gallery|access-date=2018-06-15}}</ref>- A group exhibition held at Heron Arts, San Francisco, California.\n* 2019, ''IN THE MAKING''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://retroafrica.com/|title=IN THE MAKING|work=Retro Africa Gallery|access-date=2018-07-05}}</ref>- A Contemporary Art Exhibition held at Retro Africa Gallery, Abuja, Nigeria.\n* 2019, ''LAX-MSY''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thinkspaceprojects.com/shows/lax-msy/|title=LAX / MSY|work=Thinkspace Gallery|access-date=2018-08-10}}</ref>- A group exhibition held at Red Truck Gallery, New Orleans, Louisiana.\n* 2019, ''LAX-LHR''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thinkspaceprojects.com/shows/lax-lhr/|title=LAX / LHR|work=Thinkspace Gallery|access-date=2018-09-03}}</ref>- Co-Curated Exhibition with Stolen Space held at Osborn Street, London.\n* 2019, ''Art X'' Lagos<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://artxlagos.com/artists/ken-nwadiogbu/|title=Art X Lagos|work=Artyrama Gallery|access-date=2019-11-02}}</ref>- International Contemporary Art Fair in West Africa held at Federal Palace, Lagos, Nigeria.\n* 2019, ''Moniker'' Art Fair<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.monikerartfair.com/|title=Contemporealism|work=Premier Art Solutions|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>- A Contemporary Art Fair held at The Chelsea Sorting Office, Chelsea, London.\n* 2019, ''CONTEMPOREALISM'' Solo show <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thebricklanegallery.com/ken-nwadiogbu-contemporealism/|title=Contemporealism|work=Premier Art Solutions|access-date=2019-10-03}}</ref>- The debut International Solo Show by Ken Nwadiogbu held in Bricklane Gallery, London.\n* 2019, ''Miami Art Week''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://theartplug.net/events/|title=Miami Art Week|work=The Artplug Powerhouse|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>- A Contemporary Art Exhibition held in The Citadel, Miami, FL.\n* 2020, ''ART OF DIVERSITY''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://bridgemaneditions.com/collections/the-art-of-diversity|title=Art of Diversity|work=Bridgeman Images|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref>- A Contemporary Art Exhibition featuring winners of the Bridgeman Award, held in Yinka Sonibare CBE RA studio, London.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nwadiogbu, Ken}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Nigerian artists]]\n[[Category:University of Lagos alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Nigerian visual artist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Ken Nwadiogbu\n| image       = Ken Nwadiogbu\u2019s Profile picture.jpg\n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = Kenechukwu Emmanuel Nwadiogbu\n| birth_place = Nigerian\n| occupation  = Visual artist\n| movement    = Contemporealism\n| website     = {{URL|www.kennwadiogbu.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Ken Nwadiogbu''' (popularly known as '''KenArt''') is a Nigerian born multidisciplinary artist.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/videos/world/2018/04/03/ken-nwadiogbu-lagos-hyperrealist.cnn/|title=Ken Nwadiogbu: Nigeria's groundbreaking, hyperrealist artist|work=CNN|access-date=2018-04-05}}</ref> He calls his method contemporealism \u2013 a fusion that is primarily centered around [[Hyperrealism (visual arts)|hyper-realism]] and [[contemporary art]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kennwadiogbu.com/statement/|title=Ken Nwadiogbu: Artist Statement|work=kennwadiogbu official website|access-date=2018-04-05}}</ref> In 2019, Ken Nwadiogbu was awarded the prestigious [[The Future Awards Africa]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://awards.thefutureafrica.com/burna-boy-israel-adesanya-timini-egbuson-simi-drey-adejumo-tolani-alli-others-emerge-winners-at-the-future-awards-africa-2019/|title=winners at The Future Awards Africa 2019|work=TFAA 2019|access-date=2019-11-26}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nKenechukwu Nwadiogbu did not set out to become an artist. Born at a time when parents still choose professions for their children and fields in science were deemed the most lucrative, Nwadiogbu wanted to study civil engineering. Although, this 17-year-old Nwadiogbu's life is about to change as he discovers art in the most intriguing way- puppy love.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://guardian.ng/life/ken-nwadiogbu-the-rise-of-nigerias-contemporealist/|title=Ken Nwadiogbu: The Rise Of Nigeria\u2019s Contemporealist|work=Guardian Life|access-date=2019-09-29}}</ref>\n\nAs he developed in his drawing, his fame among his small circle grew and the encouragement from his friends spurred him on.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://guardian.ng/life/ken-nwadiogbu-the-rise-of-nigerias-contemporealist/|title=Ken Nwadiogbu: The Rise Of Nigeria\u2019s Contemporealist|work=Guardian Life|access-date=2019-09-29}}</ref>\n\nNwadiogbu attended the [[University of Lagos]], where he studied [[Civil Engineering|Civil and Environmental Engineering]]. His journey with art began in this university, and despite having no formal training, he has pushed to become an interesting contemporary artist from [[Nigeria]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thesparkng.com/hyper-realistic-drawings-kenart/|title=Hyper-realistic drawings by Kenart|work=The Spark|access-date=2018-04-04}}</ref>\n\n==Style of art==\nAccording to an interview with [[Juxtapoz Magazine]], Nwadiogbu responds on canvas to socio-political structures and issues around him and the world. Through meticulous hyperrealist technique, he constructs arresting images rich with deft use of form and space. Cleverly, his paintings regularly feature obscure portraits of everyday people peeking through the ripped paper, elevating and situating Africans in the global context. Weighty issues like gender equality, African cultures, global politics, Black power, and most recently knife-crime come to the conversation by way of his mind-boggling technique.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.juxtapoz.com/news/painting/ken-nwadiogbu-opens-his-international-debut-brick-lane-gallery-london/|title=Ken Nwadiogbu Opens His International Debut at Brick Lane Gallery, London|work=JUXTAPOZ MAGAZINE|date=2019-09-26}}</ref> Working with charcoal, pencil, and acrylic, Nwadiogbu aims to achieve a deeper meaning through his art, one which goes beyond the visually spectacular facade he presents into different themes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boredpanda.com/hyper-realistic-drawings-ken-nwadiogbu-nigeria/|title=This Nigerian Artist\u2019s Artworks Are So Realistic It\u2019s Hard To Believe He Used Nothing More Than A Pencil|work=Bored Panda|access-date=2018-02-16}}</ref>\n\nHis art is inspired by social movements and principles while evaluating, interrogating and challenging socio-political structures and issues within society. He perceives his art as a response to society and a way to inspire one or two people to re-evaluate their socio-political structures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.creativeboom.com/inspiration/ken-nwadiogbu-addresses-race-and-gender-with-his-hyperrealist-art/|title=Ken Nwadiogbu addresses issues of race and gender with his 'contemporealist' art|work=Creative Boom|date=2019-10-01}}</ref>\n===A Voice for #MeToo===\nAccording to an interview with [[CNN]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition-m.cnn.com/2018/04/06/africa/ken-nwadiogbu-hyperrealist-artist-nigeria-africa/|title=Ken Nwadiogbu: Inside Nigeria's hyperrealist art scene|work=CNN|access-date=2018-04-11}}</ref> Nwadiogbu's most recent work was a piece for the global #MeToo movement\u2014a work he's so passionate about, he completed it within 24 hours. In the #MeToo piece, two girls are wrapped in nylon, one is depressed and resigned to her fate; the other is angry and determined to push through the barrier. It's an emotional piece, born from thoughtfulness and his passion to give young African girls a voice.\n\n\"I want the African girl to be like the second girl (in the painting) who is saying, 'I want to speak out. I want to loud my consciousness. I want to loud who I am.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition-m.cnn.com/2018/04/06/africa/ken-nwadiogbu-hyperrealist-artist-nigeria-africa/|title=Ken Nwadiogbu: Inside Nigeria's hyperrealist art scene|work=CNN|access-date=2018-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and residencies==\n*2019: [[The Future Awards Africa]] Prize for Art (Visual/Applied)<ref>[http://https://www.herald.ng/2019-future-awards-africa-winners/\"2019 Future Awards Africa \u2013 Complete List of Winners\"], The Herald. 25 November 2019.</ref>\n*2019: The Bridgeman Studio Award (Grand Prize winner)<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.bridgemanimages.co.uk/en/12695/bridgeman-studio-award-2019-winner-ken-nwadiogbu-interview/|title= Bridgeman Studio Award 2019 Winner: Ken Nwadiogbu Interview|access-date=2020-01-20|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions==\n* 2016, ''Insanity''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2016/12/creating-platform-devt-young-artists-frank-momoh/|title=We\u2019re creating platform for devt of young artists \u2014Frank Momoh - Vanguard News|date=2016-12-17|work=Vanguard News|access-date=2018-02-07}}</ref>- Sponsored by Frot Foundation. Held at [[Omenka Gallery]], Ikoyi, Lagos, Nigeria.\n* 2017, ''It's Not Furniture''<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pulse.ng/lifestyle/food-travel-arts-culture/its-not-furniture-exhibition-reveals-art-as-a-representation-of-young-contemporary-individuals-id6717009.html|title=It\"s Not Furniture: Exhibition reveals art as a representation of young contemporary individuals|last=Omotosho|first=Kehinde|access-date=2018-02-07}}</ref> - Sponsored by Temple Management Company. Held at Omenka Gallery,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://visual.ng/2017/05/25/its-not-furniture-exhibition-opens-at-omenka-gallery-in-lagos/|title=\u2018It\u2019s NOT furniture\u2019 exhibition opens at Omenka Gallery in Lagos|date=2017-05-25|work=Visual Magazine|access-date=2018-02-07}}</ref> Ikoyi, Lagos, Nigeria.\n* 2017, ''Finding your Identity'' - Sponsored by ENACOF. Held at British Council, Abuja, Nigeria.\n* 2017, ''ARTYRAMA'' Art Exhibition<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thisdaylive.com/index.php/2017/12/09/artyrama-hosts-digital-art-gallery/|title=Artyrama Hosts Digital Art Gallery|last=Editor|first=Online|date=2017-12-09|work=THISDAYLIVE|access-date=2018-02-07}}</ref>- Curated by Jess Castellote. Held at Alhaji Bashorun, Ikoyi, Lagos, Nigeria.\n* 2018, ''EMPOWERMENT'' Exhibition<ref>{{Cite news|url=http