Retro Africa Gallery|access-date=2018-07-05}}</ref>- A Contemporary Art Exhibition held at Retro Africa Gallery, Abuja, Nigeria.\n* 2019, ''LAX-MSY''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thinkspaceprojects.com/shows/lax-msy/|title=LAX / MSY|work=Thinkspace Gallery|access-date=2018-08-10}}</ref>- A group exhibition held at Red Truck Gallery, New Orleans, Louisiana.\n* 2019, ''LAX-LHR''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thinkspaceprojects.com/shows/lax-lhr/|title=LAX / LHR|work=Thinkspace Gallery|access-date=2018-09-03}}</ref>- Co-Curated Exhibition with Stolen Space held at Osborn Street, London.\n* 2019, ''Art X'' Lagos<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://artxlagos.com/artists/ken-nwadiogbu/|title=Art X Lagos|work=Artyrama Gallery|access-date=2019-11-02}}</ref>- International Contemporary Art Fair in West Africa held at Federal Palace, Lagos, Nigeria.\n* 2019, ''Moniker'' Art Fair<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.monikerartfair.com/|title=Contemporealism|work=Premier Art Solutions|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>- A Contemporary Art Fair held at The Chelsea Sorting Office, Chelsea, London.\n* 2019, ''CONTEMPOREALISM'' Solo show <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thebricklanegallery.com/ken-nwadiogbu-contemporealism/|title=Contemporealism|work=Premier Art Solutions|access-date=2019-10-03}}</ref>- The debut International Solo Show by Ken Nwadiogbu held in Bricklane Gallery, London.\n* 2019, ''Miami Art Week''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://theartplug.net/events/|title=Miami Art Week|work=The Artplug Powerhouse|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>- A Contemporary Art Exhibition held in The Citadel, Miami, FL.\n* 2020, ''ART OF DIVERSITY''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://bridgemaneditions.com/collections/the-art-of-diversity|title=Art of Diversity|work=Bridgeman Images|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref>- A Contemporary Art Exhibition featuring winners of the Bridgeman Award, held in Yinka Sonibare CBE RA studio, London.\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nwadiogbu, Ken}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Nigerian artists]]\n[[Category:University of Lagos alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "http", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ken_Nwadiogbu"}
{"title_page": "Progress MS-12", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name          = Progress MS-12\n| image         = ISS-60 Progress MS-12 approaches the ISS.jpg\n| image_caption = Progress MS-12 approaches the ISS\n\n| COSPAR_ID        = 2019-047A\n| SATCAT           = 44455\n| mission_duration = {{time interval|2019-07-31 12:10|2019-11-29 14:11|show=dhm|abbr=on}} <ref name=russianspaceweb/>\n| mission_type     = [[International Space Station|ISS]] resupply\n| operator         = [[Roscosmos State Corporation|Roscosmos]]\n| manufacturer     = [[RKK Energia]]\n\n| spacecraft       = Progress MS-12 (No.442)\n| spacecraft_type  = [[Progress-MS]]\n| launch_mass      = 7281 kg\n| dry_mass         = <!--spacecraft mass in orbit without fuel-->\n| payload_mass     = <!--Mass of cargo carried by spacecraft (eg. for Space Shuttle), or total mass of instrumentation/equipment/experiments for mission-->\n| dimensions       = <!--body dimensions and solar array span-->\n| power            = <!--end-of-life power, in watts-->\n\n| launch_date       = 31 July 2019, 12:10:46 [[UTC]] <ref name=Exp60/>\n| launch_rocket     = [[Soyuz-2.1a]]\n| launch_site       = [[Baikonur Cosmodrome|Baikonur]], [[Baikonur Cosmodrome|Site 31/6]]\n| launch_contractor = [[Roscosmos State Corporation|Roscosmos]]\n\n| docking = {{Infobox spaceflight/Dock\n   | docking_target     = [[International Space Station|ISS]]\n   | docking_type       = dock\n   | docking_port       = [[Pirs (ISS module)|Pirs]]\n   | docking_date       = 31 July 2019, 15:29 [[UTC]] <ref name=Exp60>[http://www.spacefacts.de/iss/english/exp_60.htm SpaceFacts]</ref>\n   | undocking_date     = 29 November 2019 10:25 UTC <ref name=russianspaceweb/>\n   | time_docked        = {{time interval|2019-07-31 15:29|2019-11-29 10:25|show=dhm|abbr=on}}\n }}\n\n<!--Cargo parameters-->| payload_items = <!--Major individual items (e.g. satellites deployed, etc)-->\n| cargo_mass         = 2436 kg <!--Mass of the cargo aboard-->\n| cargo_mass_press   = 1230 kg <!--Mass of pressurised cargo-->\n| cargo_mass_unpress = <!--Mass of unpressurised cargo (e.g. Dragon Trunk)-->\n| cargo_mass_fuel    = 705 kg <!--Mass of fuel transferred from spacecraft's tanks-->\n| cargo_mass_gas     = 51 kg <!--Mass of gasses transferred (e.g. oxygen)-->\n| cargo_mass_water   = 420 kg <!--Mass of water transferred-->\n\n| programme          = Progress ISS Resupply\n| previous_mission   = [[Progress MS-11]]\n| next_mission       = [[Progress MS-13]]\n\n<!--mission insignia or patch-->| insignia = <!--omit the \"file\" prefix-->\n| insignia_caption = <!--image caption-->\n| insignia_alt     = <!--image alt text-->\n| insignia_size    = <!--include px/em; defaults to 180px-->\n}}\n\n'''Progress MS-12''' ({{Lang-ru|\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0441 \u041cC-12|italic=yes}}), identified by [[NASA]] as '''Progress 73''' or '''73P''', was a [[Progress (spacecraft)|Progress]] spacecraft used by [[Roscosmos State Corporation|Roscosmos]] to resupply the [[International Space Station]] (ISS).<ref name=russianspaceweb>http://russianspaceweb.com/progress-ms-12.html</ref>\n\n==Launch==\nThe launch was planned for 1 July 2018, rescheduled for 5 June 2019 and rescheduled to 31 July 2019.<ref>{{cite report|author=NASA Office of Inspector General|date=June 28, 2016|title=NASA's Response to SpaceX's June 2015 Launch Failure: Impacts on Commercial Resupply of the International Space Station|url=https://oig.nasa.gov/audits/reports/FY16/IG-16-025.pdf|publisher=NASA Office of Inspector General |format=PDF|issue=Report No. IG-16-025|page=13|access-date=2016-07-18}} {{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\nProgress MS-12 was launched in 31 July 2019 12:10:46 UTC from [[Baikonur Cosmodrome]] in [[Kazakhstan]], using a [[Soyuz-2.1a]] rocket.<ref name=russianspaceweb/>\n\n==Docking==\nProgress MS-12 docked with the [[Pirs (ISS module)|Pirs]] docking module. The docking took place 3 hours 18 minutes 31 seconds into the mission (a new record time).\n\n==Cargo==\nThe Progress MS-12 spacecraft delivered {{convert|1164|kg}} of dry cargo (in the cargo compartment), {{convert|420|kg}} of water (in the Rodnik-system tanks), {{convert|51|kg}} of oxygen (in pressurized bottles), {{convert|850|kg}} of propellant in the refueling section and {{convert|880|kg}} of propellant in the integrated propulsion system to the International Space Station. The dry cargo consisted of: {{convert|394|kg}} of hardware for onboard systems, {{convert|27|kg}} of medical supplies, {{convert|1|kg}} of personal protective gear, {{convert|190|kg}} of hygiene items, {{convert|7|kg}} of repairs and servicing equipment, {{convert|20|kg}} of means of crew support, {{convert|282|kg}} of food, {{convert|13|kg}} of payloads, {{convert|38|kg}} of structural components and other hardware and {{convert|192|kg}} of NASA cargo.<ref name=russianspaceweb/>\n\n==End of mission==\nThe Progress craft undocked from ISS 29 November 2019 10:25 UTC, initiated braking maneuver 13:39 UTC, re-entered Earth's atmosphere 14:11 UTC (end of mission), with any remaining debris impacting a remote part of Pacific Ocean 14:19 UTC.<ref name=russianspaceweb/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n{{Progress spacecraft}}\n{{Unmanned ISS resupply flights}}\n{{Orbital launches in 2019}}\n\n[[Category:Progress (spacecraft) missions]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 2019]]\n[[Category:2019 in Russia]]\n[[Category:Supply vehicles for the International Space Station]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched by Soyuz-2 rockets]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft which reentered in 2019]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name          = Progress MS-12\n| image         = ISS-60 Progress MS-12 approaches the ISS.jpg\n| image_caption = Progress MS-12 approaches the ISS\n\n| COSPAR_ID        = 2019-047A\n| SATCAT           = 44455\n| mission_duration = {{time interval|2019-07-31 12:10|2019-11-29 14:11|show=dhm|abbr=on}} <ref name=russianspaceweb/>\n| mission_type     = [[International Space Station|ISS]] resupply\n| operator         = [[Roscosmos State Corporation|Roscosmos]]\n| manufacturer     = [[RKK Energia]]\n\n| spacecraft       = Progress MS-12 (No.442)\n| spacecraft_type  = [[Progress-MS]]\n| launch_mass      = 7281 kg\n| dry_mass         = <!--spacecraft mass in orbit without fuel-->\n| payload_mass     = <!--Mass of cargo carried by spacecraft (eg. for Space Shuttle), or total mass of instrumentation/equipment/experiments for mission-->\n| dimensions       = <!--body dimensions and solar array span-->\n| power            = <!--end-of-life power, in watts-->\n\n| launch_date       = 31 July 2019, 12:10:46 [[UTC]] <ref name=Exp60/>\n| launch_rocket     = [[Soyuz-2.1a]]\n| launch_site       = [[Baikonur Cosmodrome|Baikonur]], [[Baikonur Cosmodrome|Site 31/6]]\n| launch_contractor = [[Roscosmos State Corporation|Roscosmos]]\n\n| docking = {{Infobox spaceflight/Dock\n   | docking_target     = [[International Space Station|ISS]]\n   | docking_type       = dock\n   | docking_port       = [[Pirs (ISS module)|Pirs]]\n   | docking_date       = 31 July 2019, 15:29 [[UTC]] <ref name=Exp60>[http://www.spacefacts.de/iss/english/exp_60.htm SpaceFacts]</ref>\n   | undocking_date     = 29 November 2019 10:25 UTC <ref name=russianspaceweb/>\n   | time_docked        = {{time interval|2019-07-31 15:29|2019-11-29 10:25|show=dhm|abbr=on}}\n }}\n\n<!--Cargo parameters-->| payload_items = <!--Major individual items (e.g. satellites deployed, etc)-->\n| cargo_mass         = 2436 kg <!--Mass of the cargo aboard-->\n| cargo_mass_press   = 1230 kg <!--Mass of pressurised cargo-->\n| cargo_mass_unpress = <!--Mass of unpressurised cargo (e.g. Dragon Trunk)-->\n| cargo_mass_fuel    = 705 kg <!--Mass of fuel transferred from spacecraft's tanks-->\n| cargo_mass_gas     = 51 kg <!--Mass of gasses transferred (e.g. oxygen)-->\n| cargo_mass_water   = 420 kg <!--Mass of water transferred-->\n\n| programme          = Progress ISS Resupply\n| previous_mission   = [[Progress MS-11]]\n| next_mission       = [[Progress MS-13]]\n\n<!--mission insignia or patch-->| insignia = <!--omit the \"file\" prefix-->\n| insignia_caption = <!--image caption-->\n| insignia_alt     = <!--image alt text-->\n| insignia_size    = <!--include px/em; defaults to 180px-->\n}}\n\n'''Progress MS-12''' ({{Lang-ru|\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0441 \u041cC-12|italic=yes}}), identified by [[NASA]] as '''Progress 73''' or '''73P''', was a [[Progress (spacecraft)|Progress]] spacecraft used by [[Roscosmos State Corporation|Roscosmos]] to resupply the [[International Space Station]] (ISS).<ref name=russianspaceweb>http://russianspaceweb.com/progress-ms-12.html</ref>\n\n==Launch==\nThe launch was planned for 1 July 2018, rescheduled for 5 June 2019 and rescheduled to 31 July 2019.<ref>{{cite report|author=NASA Office of Inspector General|date=June 28, 2016|title=NASA's Response to SpaceX's June 2015 Launch Failure: Impacts on Commercial Resupply of the International Space Station|url=https://oig.nasa.gov/audits/reports/FY16/IG-16-025.pdf|publisher=NASA Office of Inspector General |format=PDF|issue=Report No. IG-16-025|page=13|access-date=2016-07-18}} {{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\nProgress MS-12 was launched in 31 July 2019 12:10:46 UTC from [[Baikonur Cosmodrome]] in [[Kazakhstan]], using a [[Soyuz-2.1a]] rocket.<ref>http://russianspaceweb.com/progress-ms-12.html</ref>\n\n==Docking==\nProgress MS-12 docked with the [[Pirs (ISS module)|Pirs]] docking module. The docking took place 3 hours 18 minutes 31 seconds into the mission (a new record time).\n\n==Cargo==\nThe Progress MS-12 spacecraft delivered {{convert|1164|kg}} of dry cargo (in the cargo compartment), {{convert|420|kg}} of water (in the Rodnik-system tanks), {{convert|51|kg}} of oxygen (in pressurized bottles), {{convert|850|kg}} of propellant in the refueling section and {{convert|880|kg}} of propellant in the integrated propulsion system to the International Space Station. The dry cargo consisted of: {{convert|394|kg}} of hardware for onboard systems, {{convert|27|kg}} of medical supplies, {{convert|1|kg}} of personal protective gear, {{convert|190|kg}} of hygiene items, {{convert|7|kg}} of repairs and servicing equipment, {{convert|20|kg}} of means of crew support, {{convert|282|kg}} of food, {{convert|13|kg}} of payloads, {{convert|38|kg}} of structural components and other hardware and {{convert|192|kg}} of NASA cargo.<ref>http://russianspaceweb.com/progress-ms-12.html</ref>\n\n==End of mission==\nThe Progress craft undocked from ISS 29 November 2019 10:25 UTC, initiated braking maneuver 13:39 UTC, re-entered Earth's atmosphere 14:11 UTC (end of mission), with any remaining debris impacting a remote part of Pacific Ocean 14:19 UTC.<ref name=russianspaceweb/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n{{Progress spacecraft}}\n{{Unmanned ISS resupply flights}}\n{{Orbital launches in 2019}}\n\n[[Category:Progress (spacecraft) missions]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 2019]]\n[[Category:2019 in Russia]]\n[[Category:Supply vehicles for the International Space Station]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched by Soyuz-2 rockets]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft which reentered in 2019]]\n", "name_user": "CRS-20", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Progress_MS-12"}
{"title_page": "2007 St. Louis Cardinals season", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox MLB yearly\n| name = St. Louis Cardinals\n| season = 2007\n| misc = \n| image = St Louis Cardinals Cap Insignia.svg\n| logo = Saint Louis Cardinals Logo.png\n| current league = National League\n| y1 = 1892\n| division = [[National League Central|Central Division]]\n| y2 = 1994\n| Uniform logo =\n| ballpark = [[Busch Stadium]]\n| y4 = 2006\n| city = [[St. Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]], Missouri\n| y5 = 1882\n| record = 78\u201384 (.481)\n| divisional place = 3rd\n| owners = [[William DeWitt, Jr.]], Fred Hanser\n| general managers = [[Walt Jocketty]]\n| presidents = [[Mark Lamping]]\n| genmanagers = [[Walt Jocketty]]\n| managers = [[Tony La Russa]]\n| television = [[Fox Sports Net|FSN Midwest]]<br>([[Dan McLaughlin]], [[Al Hrabosky]], [[Joe Buck]])<br>[[KSDK]]<br>([[Jay Randolph]], [[Ricky Horton]])\n| radio = [[KTRS (AM)|KTRS]]<br>([[Mike Shannon]], [[John Rooney (sportscaster)|John Rooney]])\n|}}\n\nThe '''[[St. Louis Cardinals]] 2007 season''' was the team's 126th season in [[St. Louis, Missouri]] and the 116th season in the [[National League]]. The season started with the team trying to defend their [[2006 World Series]] championship.  During the offseason, the Cardinals were faced with the challenge of handling their starting rotation.  Four of their five starters were free agents, including [[Jeff Suppan]] (the [[2006 National League Championship Series|2006 NLCS]] MVP), [[Jeff Weaver]] (the winning pitcher in the World Series Game 5 clincher), [[Mark Mulder]], and [[Jason Marquis]].  In the end, Suppan, Weaver, and Marquis all signed with other teams.  The Cardinals signed Mulder, who ended the 2006 season on the [[disabled list]], to a new two-year contract, but Mulder remained on the disabled list after undergoing shoulder surgery.<ref>{{cite web | title = Cardinals sign Mulder to two-year deal | work = St. Louis Cardinals official website | url = http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070110&content_id=1776919&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl | accessdate = May 14, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nTo replace the departed pitchers, the Cardinals promoted [[Adam Wainwright]], who spent 2006 in relief and took the closer's job from injured [[Jason Isringhausen]], to the rotation.  They signed free agent pitcher [[Kip Wells]] to fill another spot.  The team entered 2007 with a rotation of [[Chris Carpenter]], Wells, Wainwright and [[Anthony Reyes]], with reliever [[Braden Looper]] assuming the fifth starter's role until Mulder's return.<ref>{{cite web | title = Notes: Starting five are finalized | work = St. Louis Cardinals official website | url = http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070321&content_id=1853372&vkey=spt2007news&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl | accessdate = June 2, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn contrast with the rotation, the rest of the team remained stable.  Every member of the Cardinals' playoff bullpen remained under contract for 2007, though the Cardinals signed free agent relievers [[Ryan Franklin]] and [[Russ Springer]] for reinforcement<ref>{{cite web | title = Notes: Franklin needs to earn spot | work = St. Louis Cardinals official website | url = http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070218&content_id=1806300&vkey=spt2007news&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl | accessdate = June 2, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Springer relishes role as mentor | work = St. Louis Cardinals official website | url = http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070227&content_id=1818307&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl | accessdate = June 2, 2007 }}</ref> and middle reliever [[Josh Kinney]] suffered an injury in spring training that required [[Tommy John surgery]] and forced him to miss the entire 2007 season.<ref>{{cite web|author =Matthew Leach |others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070308&content_id=1834049&vkey=spt2007news&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: Kinney to have Tommy John surgery |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |date=January 2, 2011 |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref> Every position player for the Cardinals returned in 2007 except for midseason acquisition [[Ronnie Belliard]], who signed as a free agent with the [[Washington Nationals]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Belliard ready to help Nationals | work = Washington Nationals official website | url = http://washington.nationals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070227&content_id=1819141&vkey=spt2007news&fext=.jsp&c_id=was | accessdate = May 14, 2007 }}</ref>  To replace Belliard, the Cardinals signed [[Adam Kennedy]], a former Cardinal who was traded to the then-[[Anaheim Angels]] for [[Jim Edmonds]] in 2000, and was teammates with current Cardinals [[David Eckstein]] and [[Scott Spiezio]] when they won the [[2002 World Series]] with Anaheim.<ref>{{cite web | title = Former teammates Eckstein, Kennedy have great chemistry  | work = St. Louis Cardinals official website | url = http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070117&content_id=1780870&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl | accessdate = June 2, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn [[Spring training]], the Birds were 16\u201310\u20133 with a team [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]] of .255 and a 2.29 team [[Earned run average|ERA]].  Attendance at [[Roger Dean Stadium]] was 102,619.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://presspass.mlb.com/dbdocs/77/129/3700_1730.pdf |title=St. Louis Cardinals GAME NOTES |date=March 6, 2008 |accessdate=March 6, 2008 |publisher=St. Louis Cardinals|format=PDF}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n==Regular season==\n\n===April: The death of Josh Hancock===\nThe Cardinals began the season by raising their championship banner for winning the [[2006 World Series]].  They played the first game of the 2007 season in a rematch of the [[2006 National League Championship Series|2006 NLCS]] as they hosted the [[New York Mets|Mets]] for a three-game series.  The homestand ended with disappointment, however, as the Mets swept the Cardinals, outscoring them 20\u20132.<ref>{{cite web | title = Cards' bats quiet in third straight loss | work = St. Louis Cardinals official website | url = http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/gameday_recap.jsp?ymd=20070404&content_id=1878765&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl | accessdate = June 2, 2007 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070426153350/http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/gameday_recap.jsp?ymd=20070404&content_id=1878765&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl| archivedate= April 26, 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref>  Later in April the Cardinals suffered a major setback when ace pitcher [[Chris Carpenter]] was placed on the [[disabled list]] due to arthritis and impingement.<ref>{{cite web | title = Carpenter on DL with elbow injury | work = Major League Baseball official website | url = http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070409&content_id=1888840&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb | accessdate = May 14, 2007 }}</ref>  The team struggled for most of the month of April, getting off to a 10\u201314 start.\n\nAt approximately 12:35&nbsp;am [[Central Time Zone|CST]] on April 29, 2007, [[pitcher]] [[Josh Hancock]] died in a car accident in [[St. Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Cardinals mourn passing of Hancock | work = St. Louis Cardinals official website | url = http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070429&content_id=1936685&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl | accessdate = May 14, 2007 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070516071829/http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070429&content_id=1936685&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl| archivedate= May 16, 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref>  Hancock, a 29-year-old reliever who threw 77 innings for the Cardinals during the 2006 season, collided with a tow truck stopped on [[Interstate 64]] to assist another motorist.  The Cardinals' game against the [[Chicago Cubs|Cubs]] scheduled for later that day was postponed due to the accident.<ref>{{cite web | title = Cubs-Cardinals game postponed | work = St. Louis Cardinals official website | url = http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070429&content_id=1936604&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl | accessdate = May 14, 2007 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070501043831/http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070429&content_id=1936604&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl| archivedate= May 1, 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref>  Autopsy reports showed that Hancock was intoxicated with a [[blood alcohol level]] almost twice the legal limit in [[Missouri]].<ref>{{cite web | title = A night of fatal mistakes for Josh Hancock | work = stltoday.com St. Louis Post-Dispatch | url = http://www.stltoday.com/stltoday/sports/stories.nsf/cardinals/story/E809029F139BB9E1862572D2001B02A9?OpenDocument | accessdate = May 14, 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070508023341/http://www.stltoday.com/stltoday/sports/stories.nsf/cardinals/story/E809029F139BB9E1862572D2001B02A9?OpenDocument| archivedate= May 8, 2007 | url-status= dead}}</ref>  In response the Cardinals banned alcohol from the team's clubhouse.<ref>{{cite web | title = Cardinals ban alcohol in clubhouse | work = St. Louis Cardinals Official website | url = http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070504&content_id=1946145&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl | accessdate = May 14, 2007 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070509040818/http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070504&content_id=1946145&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl| archivedate= May 9, 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref>  The tragedy brought back memories of the loss of former Cardinal pitcher [[Darryl Kile]], who died of coronary disease in 2002.  Hancock became the second [[Major League Baseball|MLB]] player in the previous 25 years to die during the regular season.<ref>{{cite web | title = Tragic deaths of Major Leaguers | work = St. Louis Cardinals Official website | url = http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070429&content_id=1937003&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl | accessdate = May 14, 2007 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070502051809/http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070429&content_id=1937003&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl| archivedate= May 2, 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref>  After Hancock's death, the Cardinals began wearing a black patch reading \"32\" on their uniforms in his memory.\n\n===May===\nThe team's offensive struggles grew worse with the start of the new month.  St. Louis went two weeks without hitting a [[home run]]; [[Chris Duncan]] hit one in a loss to the [[Milwaukee Brewers|Brewers]] on May 1 and again in a May 15 victory over the [[Los Angeles Dodgers|Dodgers]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Cards back Thompson in LA opener | work = St. Louis Cardinals official website | url = http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/gameday_recap.jsp?ymd=20070515&content_id=1965552&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl | accessdate = May 14, 2007 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070518081935/http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/gameday_recap.jsp?ymd=20070515&content_id=1965552&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl| archivedate= May 18, 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref>  On May 13, they were shut out for the sixth time in their first 35 games in a 3\u20130 loss to the [[San Diego Padres|Padres]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Cards' bats silent in loss to Padres | work = St. Louis Cardinals official website | url = http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/gameday_recap.jsp?ymd=20070513&content_id=1962477&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl | accessdate = June 2, 2007 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070518081914/http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/gameday_recap.jsp?ymd=20070513&content_id=1962477&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl| archivedate= May 18, 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref>  A series in Detroit featuring a rematch of the teams from the 2006 World Series ended in a three-game Tiger sweep and dropped the Cardinals' record to 16\u201325 for the season.<ref>{{cite web | title = Cards downed in finale vs. Tigers | work = St. Louis Cardinals official website | url = http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/gameday_recap.jsp?ymd=20070520&content_id=1976253&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl | accessdate = June 2, 2007 }}</ref>  [[Anthony Reyes]] was sent down to the minors on May 27 after compiling an 0\u20138 record and 6.08 ERA.<ref>{{cite web | title = Notes: Reyes optioned; Cate recalled  | work = St. Louis Cardinals official website | url = http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070527&content_id=1988974&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl | accessdate = June 4, 2007 }}</ref>  Catcher [[Yadier Molina]] was placed on the disabled list on May 30 with a fractured wrist suffered from a foul tip that struck his hand while catching.<ref>{{cite web | title = Molina on DL with fractured left wrist | work = St. Louis Cardinals official website | url = http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070530&content_id=1994598&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl | accessdate = June 2, 2007 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070601161906/http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070530&content_id=1994598&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl| archivedate= June 1, 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref>  The team ended May with a 22\u201329 record.\n\n===June===\nKip Wells' terrible season continued on June 2, becoming the majors' first 10-game loser, and the first Cardinals pitcher in 16 years to lose ten games before the All-Star break.<ref>{{cite web | title = All not Wells as Cardinals fall  | work = St. Louis Cardinals official website | url = http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/gameday_recap.jsp?ymd=20070602&content_id=2000716&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl | accessdate = June 4, 2007 }}</ref>  Wells went to the bullpen shortly thereafter.<ref>{{cite web|author =Anthony DiComo|others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070627&content_id=2052579&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: Notes: Rotation remains in flux |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref> Looper went on the DL on June 18, after struggling following a hot start to the season.<ref>{{cite web|author =Daniel Berk |others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070618&content_id=2034823&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: Notes: Looper placed on DL |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>  Kennedy lost the starting second base job to [[Aaron Miles]].<ref>{{cite web|author =Daniel Berk |others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070619&content_id=2036765&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: Notes: Slumping Kennedy sits |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>  The Cardinals, whose starting rotation had fallen to dead last in the NL in [[earned run average|ERA]], acquired [[Mike Maroth]] from the [[Detroit Tigers]] for a player to be named later.<ref>{{cite web|author =Matthew Leach |others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070622&content_id=2042251&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: Cards acquire Maroth from Tigers |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |date=January 2, 2011 |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>  Injuries continued to plague the team as Eckstein,<ref>{{cite web|author =Matthew Leach |others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070616&content_id=2030580&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: Notes: Cards call up Ryan, Reyes |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref> Johnson<ref>{{cite web|author =Matthew Leach |others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070623&content_id=2044579&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: Notes: Johnson's DL stint starts Monday |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref> and Edmonds<ref>{{cite web|author =Daniel Berk |others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070618&content_id=2034697&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: Edmonds sidelined with pinched nerve |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref> went on the disabled list.  Anthony Reyes, recalled from the minors, dropped to 0\u201310 after a loss to the Mets on June 28.<ref>{{cite web|author =Anthony DiCom|others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/gameday_recap.jsp?ymd=20070627&content_id=2052590&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: St. Louis Cardinals News |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>  New acquisition [[Troy Percival]], a veteran relief pitcher who had been retired at the start of the season but signed a minor-league deal with St. Louis, earned a victory in his first big-league appearance in two years on June 29 against Cincinnati.<ref>{{cite web|author =Matthew Leach|others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/gameday_recap.jsp?ymd=20070629&content_id=2056277&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: St. Louis Cardinals News |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>  (Percival became the fourth member of the 2002 World Champion Angels to play on the Cardinals, joining Kennedy, Spiezio and Eckstein, and the fifth ex-Angel overall, also including Edmonds).\n\nDespite the injuries and the turnover in the pitching staff, the Cardinals played better in June, going 13\u201313 for the month after losing records in April and May.  However, they were still well behind the Brewers.  On June 30 they fell 10.5 games behind Milwaukee, the furthest out of first place they were all season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/games/standings.cgi?date=2007-06-30 |title=Historical Standings \u2013 Saturday, Jun 30, 2007 |publisher=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===July===\nAnthony Reyes was sent down to the minor leagues again on July 2.<ref>{{cite web|author =Daniel Berk|others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070702&content_id=2062501&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: Reyes headed back to Memphis |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |date=January 2, 2011 |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>\nSt. Louis entered the All-Star Break with a 40\u201345 record, in third place in the division, 7\u00bd games behind Milwaukee.  Albert Pujols was the only Cardinal on the NL All-Star roster.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/events/all_star/y2007/roster_team.jsp |title=The Official Site of Major League Baseball: Events: 2007 All-Star Game: Rosters by Team |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=January 2, 2011 |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref> St. Louis participated in another franchise's milestone when their 10\u20132 defeat of [[Philadelphia Phillies|Philadelphia]] on July 15 made the Phillies the first team in MLB history to lose 10,000 games.<ref>{{cite web|author =Stephen Fastenau|others=MLB.com |url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/gameday_recap.jsp?ymd=20070715&content_id=2089066&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi |title=The Official Site of The Philadelphia Phillies: News: Philadelphia Phillies News |publisher=Philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Cardinals could not find consistency for most of July, never losing or winning more than two games in a row until the end of the month.  The team suffered a devastating setback when Carpenter, who had been on track to return sometime in late July, was diagnosed with ligament damage and had season-ending [[Tommy John surgery]].<ref>{{cite web|author =Daniel Berk|others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070724&content_id=2106458&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: Notes: Carpenter has surgery |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>  Jim Edmonds returned to the team after spending over a month on the disabled list.<ref>{{cite web|author =Matthew Leach|others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070719&content_id=2097282&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: Notes: Edmonds rejoins Cards lineup |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>  New pitcher Mike Maroth struggled terribly in July, posting an 11.86 ERA for the month.  However, Anthony Reyes, called up to the big leagues again, got his first win of the year on July 28 after an 0\u201310 start.<ref>{{cite web|author =Matthew Leach|others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/gameday_recap.jsp?ymd=20070728&content_id=2115320&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: St. Louis Cardinals News |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn yet another attempt to bolster their faltering rotation, on July 31 St. Louis acquired [[Joel Pi\u00f1eiro]] from the Red Sox for cash and a [[player to be named later]].<ref>{{cite web|author =Matthew Leach|others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070731&content_id=2119840&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: Cards acquire versatile righty Pineiro |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>  The Cardinals had their first winning month of the year in July, going 15\u201311.  After spending most of the month far behind Milwaukee, St. Louis took three of four from the Brewers at the end of July to close the gap to six games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/games/standings.cgi?date=2007-07-29 |title=Historical Standings \u2013 Sunday, Jul 29, 2007 |publisher=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===August===\nThe momentum built by the four-game win streak at the end of July was promptly dissipated as the Cardinals lost five in a row to Pittsburgh and Washington.  Manager Tony La Russa, in an effort to increase offensive production, on August 4 began batting Cardinal pitchers eighth in the lineup.  LaRussa as justification cited 1998, when he batted the pitcher eighth for the whole second half of the season and a team that was four games under .500 before the change played ten games over .500 after.  LaRussa's revised lineup marked the first time that any team had hit its starting pitcher anywhere other than the ninth spot in the lineup since the [[Florida Marlins]] moved [[Dontrelle Willis]] up in the batting order for a few games in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|author =Michael Phillips|others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070804&content_id=2129645&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: La Russa shakes up lineup |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |date=January 2, 2011 |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Cardinals snapped their losing streak on August 6, beating San Diego 10\u20135.  St. Louis scored ten runs on ten consecutive hits in the fifth inning, becoming the 12th team in MLB history to get ten base hits in a row.<ref>{{cite web|author =Matthew Leach|others=MLB.com |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/gameday_recap.jsp?ymd=20070806&content_id=2133570&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: St. Louis Cardinals News |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>  Three days later, [[Scott Spiezio]], the Cardinals' utilityman and third base backup, was placed on the restricted list due to unspecified substance abuse problems.  LaRussa told reporters that \"What we want more than anything else is to do whatever is best for him.\"<ref>{{cite web|author =Matthew Leach|others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070809&content_id=2139926&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: Spiezio placed on restricted list |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |date=January 2, 2011 |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>  Spiezio's replacement was both a surprise and a familiar face: [[Rick Ankiel]].  Ankiel, once a promising young pitcher for the Cardinals\u2014striking out 194 batters in 175 innings in 2000 at the age of twenty\u2014suffered a catastrophic attack of wildness in the 2000 postseason, throwing nine wild pitches and walking eleven batters in only four postseason innings.  Further wildness sent him back to the minors in 2001, and after four years struggling to overcome his wildness and subsequent injuries, Ankiel quit pitching in 2005 and announced he would try to make it back to the big leagues as a hitter.  After hitting 31 home runs in 2007 for the [[Memphis Redbirds]] (St. Louis's AAA affiliate), Ankiel was called up to the big leagues to fill Spiezio's roster spot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebaseballcube.com/players/A/Rick-Ankiel.shtml |title=Rick Ankiel Statistics |publisher=The Baseball Cube |accessdate=December 12, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110101213853/http://www.thebaseballcube.com/players/A/rick-ankiel.shtml |archivedate=January 1, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author =Daniel Berk|others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070809&content_id=2139385&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: Ankiel making Cardinals return |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |date=January 2, 2011 |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>  In his first game back, Ankiel hit a three-run homer and the Cardinals won 5\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|author =Daniel Berk|others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/gameday_recap.jsp?ymd=20070809&content_id=2140369&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: St. Louis Cardinals News |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe return of Rick Ankiel to the lineup coincided with the best stretch of play by the Cardinals in 2007.  St. Louis won five in a row and eight out of ten against L.A., San Diego and Milwaukee, advancing to two games under .500 and 2\u00bd games behind the Brewers.  Continued strong starting pitching and hot hitting from Pujols, rookie infielder [[Brendan Ryan (baseball)|Brendan Ryan]], and others propelled the Cardinals to the .500 mark on August 28, the first time since they were 6\u20136 on April 16 that they did not have a losing record.\n\nScott Rolen was forced out of the lineup due to tightness and pain in his surgically repaired shoulder.<ref>{{cite web|author =Jim Molony|others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070829&content_id=2177857&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: Notes: Shoulder may sideline Rolen |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>  Rolen decided to have season-ending shoulder surgery shortly after.<ref>{{cite web|author =Matthew Leach|others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070903&content_id=2186563&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: Notes: Rolen's season over |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>  Brendan Ryan was named the starting third baseman in Rolen's place<ref>{{cite web|author =Jim Molony|others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070830&content_id=2179199&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: Notes: Ryan learning on the fly at third |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref> and the Cardinals traded for backup infielder [[Russell Branyan]] right before the August [[trade deadline]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20070831&content_id=2181057&vkey=pr_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: Official Info: Cardinals acquire Russell Branyan from Phillies; Player-to-be-named dealt for veteran infielder/outfielder |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>  St. Louis went 15\u201313 in August and finished the month 65\u201366 and in third place in the division, two games behind the Cubs and one-half game behind Milwaukee.  The Cardinals' 8\u20135 victory over Cincinnati on the last day of the month gave [[Tony La Russa]] victory #1,042 as the Cardinal manager, passing [[Red Schoendienst]] to become the winningest Cardinal manager of all time.  In the same game, Cardinal right fielder [[Juan Encarnaci\u00f3n]] was struck in the eye and severely injured with a foul ball.  Encarnacion was diagnosed with severe injuries to his left eye and multiple fractures of the orbital bone.  The injury ended his season and is believed to be potentially career-threatening.<ref>{{cite web|author =Matthew Leach|others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070831&content_id=2181965&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: Encarnacion struck in face by foul ball |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author =Matthew Leach|others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070902&content_id=2185910&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl/ |title=The Official Site of Major League Baseball: News: Cards doc guarded on Encarnacion |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |date=January 2, 2011 |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe last off-day for the team in 2007 came on August 27, when they had four games remaining in the month, and then 31 games in September.  This set a new major-league baseball record for a team with the longest number of consecutive days played (35) at the end of the season without a day off.\n\n===September===\nThe Cardinals entered September facing a stretch run of 31 games in 30 days, due to all three off-days in the month being taken up by makeups of earlier postponements.  Former Cardinal [[Miguel Cairo]], recently signed by St. Louis after he was waived by the Yankees, was brought up to the big club as the first of the September callups.<ref>{{cite web|author =Matthew Leach|others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070831&content_id=2181278&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: Notes: Branyan joins club in St. Louis |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn September 2, the Cardinals completed a three-game sweep of Cincinnati that put them at 67\u201366, the first time they were over .500 since they were 6\u20135 after the April 15 game.  They entered the game on September 7 against the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]] with a chance to take sole possession of first place, but instead the D-backs won and went on to sweep the weekend series.  September 7 was also the day that the ''New York Daily News'' reported that Rick Ankiel received a year's worth of [[human growth hormone]] in 2004 while he was trying to come back as a pitcher.  HGH was legal at that time but has since been banned by MLB.  In response Ankiel said that he had a valid prescription and that all of his medications were taken under a doctor's care.<ref>{{cite web|author =Barry M. Bloom|others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070907&content_id=2195282&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: Ankiel responds to HGH report |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |date=January 2, 2011 |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe sweep in Arizona began a devastating slump that took the Cardinals out of contention in the NL Central.  They lost nine in a row to Arizona, Chicago, Cincinnati, and Chicago again.  The ninth loss came to the Cubs in the first game of a doubleheader on September 15, the game rescheduled from April 29 after the death of Josh Hancock.  It was the longest losing streak for the franchise since the 1980 Cardinals lost ten in a row.  The Cardinals were officially eliminated on September 21, as they lost to the visiting Houston Astros at Busch Stadium.  After being eliminated from postseason, St. Louis played out the string by going 7\u20132 the rest of the way, and finished the season with a 78\u201384 record, finishing in third place, seven games behind the NL Central winning [[2007 Chicago Cubs season|Chicago Cubs]].  It was the first losing season for the franchise since the 1999 Cardinals went 75\u201386, and as of 2019, the last losing season the team has endured. \n    \nOn September 22, 2007, hosting the Houston Astros, the Cardinals set a one-day attendance record in their new Busch Stadium with 46,237.    \n    \nIn 2007, the Cardinals drew an all-time attendance record for any year with 3,552,180 in their 81 home games (breaking their previous record set in 2005), an average of 43,854 per game.\n\n==Aftermath==\nOwner [[William DeWitt, Jr.]] fired [[Walt Jocketty]], [[General manager (baseball)|General Manager]] for the Cardinals since 1995, on October 3. Assistant GM [[John Mozeliak]] replaced Jocketty in an interim capacity<ref>{{cite web|author =Nate Latsch|others=Special to MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20071003&content_id=2247373&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: Jocketty no longer GM of Cardinals |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref> before being named the new GM on October 31, 2007.<ref>{{cite web|author =Matthew Leach|others=MLB.com |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20071031&content_id=2289603&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=The Official Site of Major League Baseball: News: Cardinals name Mozeliak new GM |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=January 2, 2011 |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>\n \nOn October 22, Manager Tony La Russa, after considering moving elsewhere when his contract expired, signed a new two-year deal guaranteeing his record 13th and 14th seasons as Cardinal manager, the longest tenure in franchise history.\n<ref>{{cite web|author =Matthew Leach|others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20071022&content_id=2275736&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: La Russa remains Cardinals manager |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |date=January 2, 2011 |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\nNo Cardinal won a [[Gold Glove]]. Perhaps the most surprising denial was to catcher [[Yadier Molina]], who was denied the award despite his .991 fielding percentage.<ref>{{cite web|author =Matthew Leach|others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20071111&content_id=2298156&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: Mailbag: No Glove love for Molina? |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |date=January 2, 2011 |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>\nBoth Molina and [[Albert Pujols]] previously (November 1) won the prestigious Fielding Bible Award, which is given to only one person at each position in the major leagues.<ref>{{cite web|author =Matthew Leach|others=MLB.com |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20071102&content_id=2291100&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=The Official Site of The St. Louis Cardinals: News: Cards snag Fielding Bible Awards |publisher=Stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com |date=January 2, 2011 |accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Season standings===\n\n====National League Central====\n{{2007 NL Central standings|highlight=St. Louis Cardinals}}\n\n====Record vs. opponents====\n{{2007 NL Record vs. opponents|team=STL}}\n\n===Roster===\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"10\" style=\"background:#c41e3a; color:#fff; text-align:center;\"| 2007 St. Louis Cardinals \n|-\n| colspan=\"10\" style=\"background:#0a2252; color:#fff; text-align:center;\"| '''Roster'''\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''Pitchers'''\n{{MLBplayer|29|[[Chris Carpenter]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|61|[[Troy Cate]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|63|[[Andy Cavazos]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|59|[[Dennis Dove]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|60|[[Brian Falkenborg]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|34|[[Randy Flores]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|31|[[Ryan Franklin]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|32|[[Josh Hancock]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|44|[[Jason Isringhausen]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|56|[[Kelvin Jim\u00e9nez]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|19|[[Tyler Johnson (baseball, born 1981)|Tyler Johnson]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|54|[[Randy Keisler]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|41|[[Braden Looper]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|46|[[Mike Maroth]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|30|[[Mark Mulder]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|40|[[Troy Percival]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|35|[[Joel Pi\u00f1eiro]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|23|[[Anthony Reyes]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|36|[[Russ Springer]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|48|[[Brad Thompson]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|50|[[Adam Wainwright]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|37|[[Tod